:::summary
Greek philosophy is the foundation of Western intellectual life — a tradition born in the city-states of ancient Greece around 600 BC, when thinkers first began seeking rational, rather than purely mythological, explanations for the world and the good life. From Thales and the pre-Socratics through Socrates, Plato, and Aristotle, to the Stoics and Neo-Platonists, the Greeks asked every fundamental question about reality, knowledge, morality, and beauty that philosophy still wrestles with today. Christian thinkers from Augustine to Aquinas drew deeply from this inheritance, weaving Greek reason into the fabric of Western theology.
:::

